**$)F$\"\"$F%F%*$)F$\"\"#F%!\"\"F$F%F-F.F%" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 
-1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 650 "In those cases where Maple did
 not find enough linear factors, there is a reason why Maple did not. \+
 Maple makes an assumption that if the coefficients of a polynomial ar
e all given exactly (as integers or rational numbers [ratios of intege
r]), then you are only interested in finding exact factors (factors wh
ere the coefficients are integers or rational numbers).  The Fundament
al Theorem of Algebra doesn't guarantee that the factors of  a polynom
ial will necessarily have the same kind of coefficients as the polynom
ial, only the polynomial can be factored.  You can force Maple to repo
rt additional (approximate) factors.  For example,  compare:" }}{PARA 
0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 10 "fa
ctor(h);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#*&,&%\"xG\"\"\"F&F&F&,&*$)
F%\"\"#F&F&\"\"&!\"\"F&" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 18 "
factor(h,sqrt(5));" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#*(,&%\"xG\"\"\"*
$\"\"&#F&\"\"#F&F&,&F%F&F'!\"\"F&,&F%F&F&F&F&" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 52 "What is the difference?  \+
The extra-term is called a " }{TEXT 280 18 "field extension.  " }
{TEXT -1 178 "Adding it tells Maple to consider additonal factors wher
e the coefficients are allowed to include elements from the field exte
nsion.  It is fairly clear from the factoriztion of " }{TEXT 281 1 "h
" }{TEXT -1 280 " all by itself that something involving  sqrt(5)  wou
ld have to be included.  However, there are problems where there is no
t a obvious clue as to which specific field extension should be added.
  If you are willing to accept an appropriate solution, then using the
 field extension " }{TEXT 282 4 "real" }{TEXT -1 179 " tells Maple to \+
factor the polynomial using a floating point approximation scheme.  Fo
r example, consider (here I am pretending I don't see that adding  sqr
t(5) would be optimal):" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG 
{PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 10 "factor(h);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" 
{XPPMATH 20 "6#*&,&%\"xG\"\"\"F&F&F&,&*$)F%\"\"#F&F&\"\"&!\"\"F&" }}}
{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 15 "factor(h,real);" }}{PARA 11 
"" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#*(,&%\"xG\"\"\"$\"+xz1OA!\"*F&F&,&F%F&$F&\"\"!F
&F&,&F%F&$\"+xz1OAF)!\"\"F&" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 
0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 91 "Finally, the Fundamental Theorem of Algebra doe
s not guarantee that a polynomial of degree " }{TEXT 283 1 "n" }{TEXT 
-1 11 " will have " }{TEXT 284 1 "n" }{TEXT -1 53 " real linear factor
s.  Rather, only hat it will have " }{TEXT 285 1 "n" }{TEXT -1 134 " l
inear factors.  What is the difference?  Some of the factors may invol
ve complex roots rather than real roots.  For example compare:" }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 
10 "factor(F);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#*(,&%\"xG\"\"\"F&!\"
\"F&,&F%F&F&F&F&,&*$)F%\"\"#F&F&F&F&F&" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" 
{MPLTEXT 1 0 18 "factor(F,sqrt(3));" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6
#*(,&%\"xG\"\"\"F&!\"\"F&,&F%F&F&F&F&,&*$)F%\"\"#F&F&F&F&F&" }}}
{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 15 "factor(F,real);" }}{PARA 11 
"" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#*(,&%\"xG\"\"\"$\"+++++5!\"*F&F&,&F%F&$F(F)!\"
