{MPLTEXT 1 0 0 "" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 380 "A related theorem about finding roots of polynomials (eq
uivalently factoring polynomials into a product of linear factors) ass
erts that if the polynomial has real coefficients -- all of the polyno
mials we have considered (and will consider) have had real coefficient
s -- then any complex roots (or factors) must occur in conjugate pairs
.  For example, both the complex factors of " }{TEXT 288 5 "F, G " }
{TEXT -1 4 "and " }{TEXT 289 2 "H " }{TEXT -1 236 "(above) all occurre
d in conjugate pairs.  Demonstrate this theorem by creating three new \+
polynomials, name them F1, G1 and H1, of degree 5, 6 and 7, resp., and
 show that the any complex factors of F1, G1 and H1 occur in conjugate
 pairs." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" 
{MPLTEXT 1 0 0 "" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 115 "For demonstration purposes it is very handy to be able t
o construct polynomials with predetermined roots.  Use the " }{TEXT 
258 6 "expand" }{TEXT -1 58 " command to construct a polynomial with r
oots   -2, 5, 5, " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "-1/2" "6#,$*&\"\"\"F%\"\"#!\"\"F'" 
}{TEXT -1 71 ", 1+I and  1-I.  (Here the \"5, 5\" indicates that 5 is \+
a \"double root\".)" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 
